<abstract abstract-type="short" xml:lang="en"><p><![CDATA[The relevance of family organization to account for the making of the brazilian working-class has not been sufficiently recognized in working class historiography. This article (written in 1984) argues that it is necessary to include private life arrangements of working-class families in order to account and understand experiences of work and politics at least until the 405.]]></p></abstract>
